⏺ This is a really sharp thesis. Let me sharpen it
   because I think you're onto something specific.
                                                  
  ---                                          
  The core claim:       
                                                  
  Mechanical engineering tasks and software
  engineering tasks are structurally equivalent in
   complexity — both require hierarchical       
  decomposition, both are simulatable, both       
  require iterative feedback. But AI performs   
  dramatically worse on mechanical tasks. Why?

  You're identifying two specific failure modes:  
   
  1. Prior scarcity — almost no Lego Technic      
  mechanism design in training data vs. enormous
  amounts of code. The model has weak priors about
   what a working escapement looks like.        
  2. Feedback interpretation gap — "TypeError on
  line 47" maps cleanly to a fix. "These two      
  pieces can't connect here" requires spatial
  reasoning to diagnose and fix. The feedback     
  signal is the same type of thing (error +     
  location) but requires fundamentally different
  capability to act on.

  And your claim is: capability #1 (task          
  decomposition, acting on feedback) is already
  largely solved by LLMs. Capability #2           
  (mechanical feedback → spatial fix) is the    
  actual bottleneck. So the gap isn't "AI can't
  plan" — it's "AI can't yet close the loop on
  spatial/physical feedback."

  ---
  Why this is a paper and not just a benchmark:
                                                  
  Most benchmark papers are: "here's a new task,
  here are scores." Yours has a thesis — a        
  specific claim about why the gap exists and what
   would close it. That's the difference between a
   leaderboard and a research contribution.     

  The paper structure writes itself:
  1. We claim mechanical and software engineering
  are structurally equivalent                     
  2. We build a benchmark to test this (Lego)
  3. We show the gap is real and large            
  4. We analyze where models fail (decomposition?
  or feedback-response?)                          
  5. We show decomposition is mostly fine,        
  feedback-response is the bottleneck             
  6. We propose what a system that closes the gap 
  looks like (RL harness / feedback interpreter) 
                                                  
