  ---                                             
  Why the thesis is solid:
                                                  
  The structural equivalence argument is the    
  strongest part. It's not obvious and it's       
  falsifiable. Most people's intuition is         
  "mechanical engineering is harder because       
  physics is hard" — your reframe is more precise:
   the task structure is similar, the feedback
  loop is what's broken. That's a cleaner and more
   useful claim.

  The "necessary and sufficient condition" framing
   is also strong. You're not saying "here's a
  marginally harder benchmark." You're saying     
  "here's the specific capability that blocks AI
  from being useful in an entire domain of
  engineering." That's a much bigger claim and if
  you can demonstrate it even partially, it's
  worth publishing.

  ---
  Why hasn't this been done before — my honest 
  read:                                           
   
  A few reasons:                                  
                                                
  1. ML researchers don't know Lego Technic. The  
  people who build benchmarks are ML people. Lego
  Technic as a substrate for mechanism design     
  isn't obvious if you're not a mechanical      
  engineering nerd. It requires knowing that Lego
  Technic actually models real mechanisms — gears,
   cams, linkages — not just aesthetics.

  2. The feedback loop problem is hard to         
  formalize. Most benchmark papers need a clean
  success metric. "Does the code run" is easy.    
  "Does this mechanism function as intended" is 
  harder to define and evaluate programmatically.
  People avoid benchmarks where the evaluator is
  hard to build.

  3. AI-for-mechanical-engineering is genuinely   
  underindexed. The field has piled into code
  generation, math, and text because that's where 
  the easy evals are and where the training data
  is dense. Mechanical engineering is data-sparse
  and eval-hard — two things that discourage
  benchmark papers.

  4. Nobody connected the software engineering    
  analogy explicitly. The framing of "these two
  tasks are structurally equivalent" requires     
  standing with one foot in SE and one foot in ME.
   Most researchers are in one camp.

  ---
  Where I'd push back slightly:
                               
  The claim that task decomposition is "already
  solved" is probably 80% true but not 100%. LLMs 
  are good at decomposition in well-trodden
  domains because they've seen thousands of       
  examples of how to break down similar problems.
  For novel mechanism design — "build a variable
  transmission" — the decomposition itself might
  also be weak, not just the feedback response.
  You'd want your ablation to actually test this
  rather than assume it.

  This doesn't undermine the thesis. It might just
   mean both problems exist, and feedback-response
   is the harder one.                             
                                                
  ---
  Bottom line: It's a real gap, the framing is
  original, and the reason it hasn't been done is 
  a combination of domain unfamiliarity, eval
  difficulty, and nobody connecting the SE        
  analogy. Those are all surmountable. The risk 
  isn't "is this interesting" — the risk is
  execution: building a good enough evaluator and
  benchmark that the results are convincing.

